Here's the recommended registration:

```csharp
// MauiProgram.cs
public static class MauiProgram
{
    public static MauiApp CreateMauiApp()
    {
        var builder = MauiApp.CreateBuilder();
        builder.UseMauiApp<App>();

        // HttpClient — singleton so connections are reused (avoid socket exhaustion)
        builder.Services.AddSingleton<HttpClient>();

        // Data service — singleton because it's stateless and wraps the shared HttpClient
        builder.Services.AddSingleton<IDataService, DataService>();

        // ViewModels — transient so each navigation gets fresh state
        builder.Services.AddTransient<MainViewModel>();
        builder.Services.AddTransient<DetailViewModel>();

        // Pages — transient so each navigation creates a new page instance
        builder.Services.AddTransient<MainPage>();
        builder.Services.AddTransient<DetailPage>();

        return builder.Build();
    }
}
```

**Why these lifetimes:**

| Registration | Lifetime | Reason |
|---|---|---|
| `HttpClient` | **Singleton** | Reuses TCP connections; avoids socket exhaustion from repeated creation |
| `IDataService` | **Singleton** | Stateless API wrapper — one instance serves the whole app, shares the single `HttpClient` |
| ViewModels | **Transient** | Each navigation should get a clean VM with fresh state (no stale data from previous visits) |
| Pages | **Transient** | Pairs with transient VMs; avoids showing stale UI when navigating back to a page |

**Key rules of thumb:**
- **Singleton** → stateless shared services, HTTP clients, caches
- **Transient** → pages & ViewModels (fresh per navigation)
- **Scoped** → rarely used in MAUI (no per-request scope like ASP.NET); avoid unless you define custom scopes

> ⚠️ Never inject a **transient** or **scoped** service into a **singleton** — the shorter-lived service effectively becomes a singleton too (captive dependency).
